title: Grateful Dead Live at Rainbow Theater on 1981-10-03
description: Alabama Getaway-> Promised Land, Peggy-O, Me & My Uncle-> Big River, Tennessee Jed-> Little Red Rooster, Bird Song, Looks Like Rain-> China Cat Sunflower-> I Know You Rider Feel Like A Stranger-> Franklin's Tower, Estimated Prophet-> Terrapin Station-> Drums-> Not Fade Away-> Morning Dew-> Around & Around-> One More Saturday Night, E: Brokedown Palace

Where's Bobby? I'd give this 4 stars but, song after song, I don't hear Bobby in the mix, as in not at all. Maybe he shows up for Estimated, but if you're a fan of his like me, as nice as Brent's playing is here, you'll wonder what happened to the rhythm guitar. I'm not the Pope so I could be missing something here in the woods--listen for yourself.

My 2nd GD concert! This was my second ever Dead concert, so it was something special for me.

The Rainbow in London is/was a very special venue - very intimate with a close balcony circling above - the Dead played well here. 

My strongest memories are of the second set, where we all got very spaced out along with the Dead...

Good show, but... This shn source sounds like it went to mp3 or something.  There's a constant digital wind chimey noise in the background for the entire show.  Listen to the beginning of Peggy-0 and you can hear what I'm talking about.

streaming with winamp, sounds hella great one of my all time faves just look at that 2nd set..well, okay the a&a and sat nite not withstanding, bur the end of the first set and ya know whut? hank hill sez this show is great ill tell ya whut.

What a night! The doors opened at 7. The show was supposed to start at 7.30, but usually at the Rainbow that would mean around 9. With the house lights on, we wandered down to the front to check the equipment. It was ten past seven and there were perhaps fifty people in the place, no seats, just empty floor. Imagine our amazement when the band came out and started playing - they were that keen, and we few felt like we were so special. The mix of Alabama was all over the place - perhaps they took the sound men by surprise too. Being English, we didn't call out during the music but listened hard and flew with them through a wonderful set, from deep quiet to spine-jarring noise. The drums close up was thrilling. It's great to  hear it again and remember that night's mutual respect, which lives on at this archive.
